    <h2 id="gelatin-vs-pectin">Gelatin vs. Pectin: Why It Matters for Gummy Candy</h2>

    <p>Gelatin is a protein derived from collagen found in the bones, skin, and connective tissue of animals — primarily pigs and cows. When dissolved in warm water and cooled, gelatin molecules form a three-dimensional network that traps liquid, creating the characteristic bouncy, elastic texture of traditional gummy bears. This animal-derived ingredient has dominated the gummy candy industry since Hans Riegel invented the gummy bear in 1922 at Haribo's factory in Bonn, Germany.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">1,300</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">monthly searches for "gelatin free gummy candy" on Google in 2026 — a <strong>340% increase since 2020</strong>. This growth is driven by rising veganism (79.5 million vegans worldwide), religious dietary requirements (halal and kosher markets worth $2.6 trillion combined), and growing consumer awareness of animal welfare issues in food production. The gelatin-free candy market is projected to reach $1.8 billion by 2028.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Pectin, the primary gelatin alternative, is a naturally occurring polysaccharide found in the cell walls of fruits — especially citrus peels and apples. When combined with sugar and acid, pectin molecules cross-link to form a gel network similar to gelatin but entirely plant-derived. The resulting texture is slightly softer and less elastic than gelatin, with a more immediate "give" when you bite down rather than the prolonged bounce of a gelatin gummy. Modern food science has closed this gap considerably, and premium pectin gummies are now nearly indistinguishable from gelatin originals in blind taste tests.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
