        <h3>100% Plant-Based</h3>
        <p>Pectin is extracted from fruit peels (citrus, apple). No animals are harmed or used in production, making pectin gummies suitable for vegans, vegetarians, and flexitarians seeking to reduce animal product consumption.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="shield" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Halal & Kosher Friendly</h3>
        <p>Pork-derived gelatin is prohibited in both halal and kosher diets. Pectin-based gummies eliminate this concern entirely, opening the candy aisle to 1.8 billion Muslims and 14 million Jews worldwide.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="heart" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Allergen Advantage</h3>
        <p>Gelatin can trigger allergic reactions in individuals with meat allergies or alpha-gal syndrome (a tick-borne allergy to mammalian meat). Pectin gummies eliminate this risk completely.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="flask" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Soluble Fiber Source</h3>
        <p>Pectin is a soluble fiber that may support digestive health and slow sugar absorption. While the amount in candy is small, it is a nutritional advantage gelatin does not provide.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A 2024 study published in <em>Food Hydrocolloids</em> compared consumer perception of pectin-based gummies versus gelatin-based gummies in a double-blind trial with 120 participants. The researchers found <strong>no statistically significant difference in overall flavor satisfaction</strong> (p = 0.47), though gelatin gummies scored 8% higher on "chewiness" and pectin gummies scored 12% higher on "fruit flavor intensity" due to the acidic environment pectin requires, which enhances fruit flavor perception.</p>
      <cite>Martinez et al., Food Hydrocolloids, 2024</cite>
    </div>

    <p>Beyond pectin, other plant-based gelling agents include agar-agar (derived from red seaweed, producing a firmer, more brittle texture), starch (tapioca or corn, creating softer, quicker-dissolving gummies), and carrageenan (from Irish moss, used in combination with other agents). Most premium gelatin-free candies use pectin or pectin-starch blends because they produce the closest approximation to traditional gummy texture. If you are specifically interested in the science of <a href="/candy/pectin-gummy-candy/">pectin gummy candy</a>, we have a dedicated deep-dive guide that covers formulation, texture differences, and the best pectin-based brands in detail.</p>

