    <h2 id="science-behind">The Science Behind Gelatin-Free Gummy Texture</h2>

    <p>The challenge of creating gelatin-free gummy candy that matches the texture of traditional gummies is fundamentally a food science problem. Gelatin forms a thermoreversible gel — meaning it melts at body temperature (approximately 98.6°F / 37°C), creating that satisfying sensation of the gummy "dissolving" as you chew. Pectin gels, by contrast, are not thermoreversible; they break apart through mechanical shearing (chewing) rather than melting. This is why pectin gummies feel slightly different in the mouth even when the firmness and chewiness are similar.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="flask" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Pectin (Citrus/Apple)</h3>
        <p>The most popular gelatin substitute. Requires sugar and acid to gel. Produces a soft, clean chew with excellent fruit flavor release. Sets at room temperature. Used by Surf Sweets, SmartSweets, and most premium brands.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="droplet" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Agar-Agar (Seaweed)</h3>
        <p>Derived from red algae. Creates a firmer, more brittle texture than pectin — snaps rather than stretches. Higher melting point (185°F) makes it heat-resistant. Common in Japanese wagashi candy and Asian gummy confections.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="sun" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Tapioca Starch</h3>
        <p>Creates a softer, more yielding chew that dissolves quickly. Often combined with pectin for a texture closer to gelatin. Used in fruit snacks (Annie's, Welch's) and as a secondary gelling agent in many vegan gummy formulas.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="dna" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Carrageenan (Irish Moss)</h3>
        <p>Extracted from red seaweed. Produces elastic, stretchy gels closer to gelatin's bounce. Often used in combination with other gelling agents. Found in Swedish Fish and some conventional gummy brands as a secondary texture modifier.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>Food scientists at major candy companies are actively developing next-generation pectin formulations that more closely replicate gelatin's unique melt-in-mouth behavior. Enzyme-modified pectin (EMP) and pectin-protein complexes are two emerging technologies that show promise in laboratory settings. Within the next 3-5 years, the texture gap between gelatin and gelatin-free gummies is expected to close almost entirely. For consumers seeking the current best in texture among gelatin-free options, <a href="/candy/pectin-gummy-candy/">pectin gummy candy</a> offers the closest match to the traditional experience.</p>

