    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Gelatin-Free Gummy Candy</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is gelatin in gummy candy made from?</summary>
      <p>Gelatin is a protein derived from the collagen in animal bones, skin, and connective tissue — primarily from pigs and cows. It is boiled, processed, dried, and ground into powder. When dissolved in warm liquid and cooled, it forms the bouncy texture of traditional gummies. Because it is animal-derived, it is not suitable for vegans, vegetarians, or those following halal/kosher diets (when pork-derived).</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What do gelatin-free gummy candies use instead?</summary>
      <p>Most use pectin (from fruit peels), agar-agar (from seaweed), starch (tapioca or corn), or carrageenan (from Irish moss). Pectin is the most common because it produces the closest texture to gelatin. Many premium brands use pectin-starch blends for optimal chewiness.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do gelatin-free gummies taste different from regular gummies?</summary>
      <p>In blind taste tests, modern gelatin-free gummies are nearly indistinguishable from gelatin gummies in flavor. The main difference is texture: pectin gummies are slightly softer and less elastic, with a more immediate chew rather than a prolonged bounce. Premium brands like Surf Sweets and Lovely Candy have closed this gap significantly.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are gelatin-free gummies healthier than regular gummies?</summary>
      <p>Not inherently — health depends on sugar content, artificial ingredients, and portion size rather than the gelling agent. However, brands choosing pectin tend to also prioritize cleaner ingredients overall. Pectin itself is a soluble fiber with minor digestive benefits. The real advantage is dietary compatibility: vegan, halal, kosher, and allergen-friendly.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How can I tell if gummy candy contains gelatin?</summary>
      <p>Check the ingredient list for "gelatin," "pork gelatin," or "beef gelatin." If you see pectin, agar, starch, or carrageenan instead, it is gelatin-free. Look for "Vegan" or "Plant-Based" certifications for certainty. Products explicitly labeled "gelatin-free" on the front are the safest bet.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are Swedish Fish gelatin-free?</summary>
      <p>Yes, Swedish Fish use modified corn starch and carnauba wax instead of gelatin. They contain no animal-derived gelling agents. However, they do contain sugar (potential bone char concern for strict vegans) and artificial colors (Red 40). Read our full analysis: <a href="/candy/is-swedish-fish-vegan/">are Swedish Fish vegan?</a></p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do gelatin-free gummies melt more easily?</summary>
      <p>Pectin gummies begin softening at 86-90°F (30-32°C), while gelatin gummies tolerate up to 95°F (35°C). In practice, this means gelatin-free gummies need cooler storage. Agar-based gummies have higher heat resistance than both. Store all gummies below 75°F for best texture.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What are the best gelatin-free gummy bears for kids?</summary>
      <p>Annie's Organic Bunny Fruit Snacks (4.7 stars, 28,900 reviews), YumEarth Organic Giggles (allergen-free, organic), and Surf Sweets Fruity Bears (free of top 8 allergens). All three prioritize clean ingredients, avoid artificial dyes, and come in kid-friendly formats.</p>
    </details>

